, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Fitz","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir John Fitz William De Barri was born in 1210, in Ireland as the son of William de Barry. He had at least 2 sons with Lady Berri Viscount Of Choumound. He died in 1261, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1210–1261":"1210–1261","1190–1261":"1190–1261","1205–Male":"1205–Surnud","–1251":"–1251","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","–1278":"–1278","1170–1225":"1170–1225","1190":"1190","1205":"1205","1225":"1225","1278":"1278","1210":"1210","1251":"1251","12